Oxidative stress in sickle cell disease; pathophysiology and potential 
implications for disease management.

Nur E(1), Biemond BJ, Otten HM, Brandjes DP, Schnog JJ; CURAMA Study Group.

Author information:
(1)Department of Internal Medicine, Slotervaart Hospital Amsterdam, The 
Netherlands. e.nur@amc.uva.nl

Sickle cell disease (SCD) is a hemoglobinopathy characterized by hemolytic 
anemia, increased susceptibility to infections and vaso-occlusion leading to a 
reduced quality of life and life expectancy. Oxidative stress is an important 
feature of SCD and plays a significant role in the pathophysiology of hemolysis, 
vaso-occlusion and ensuing organ damage in sickle cell patients. Reactive oxygen 
species (ROS) and the (end-)products of their oxidative reactions are potential 
markers of disease severity and could be targets for antioxidant therapies. This 
review will summarize the role of ROS in SCD and their potential implication for 
SCD management.

